{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937090901/0073.xml":{"full_text":"Telephone\n2200\nDETERMINED TO CURB\nMYSTERIOUS ATTACKS\nInsist Meeting in Switzerland\nFriday Wilt Achieve Definite\nResults Anyway\nMAY REINFORCE PATROLS\nRefusal of Fascist Powers\nAttend Is 'Slap' at So\nviet Russia\nParis, Sept a MP) French\nforeign officials uid toolkit they\nimairf assurances that\nBritain ml ther powers are\nwining to co operate with France\nin a Mediterranean warship pe\ntrel ml* orders to \"(ink sab\nmarine attackers.\"\nThe foreign effiee hastily\ndrafted pbas for the naval patrol\nwhich it expected Friday's Medi\nterrean \"piracy conference\" to\n(By The tooriitil fna)\nFrance and Great Britain answered\nGerman-Italian refusal to take part\nin a Mediterranean \"anti-piracy1\nconference Thursday with new de\ntermination to use their warships to\nprevent attacks on shipping.\nBoth the British and French also\nInsisted that the conference in\nSwitzerland Friday would achieve\ndefinite results\u2014despite refusal of\nFascist powers to ta|e pert.\nEven as the Fascist powers refused\nto parley, the Vtench navy ministry\nordered another destroyer division to\nbe ready to rush to the Mediter\nranean. The order told commanders\nto be ready to sail on a moment's no\ntice to reinforce the fleet already on\npatrol against submarine \"piracy.'\nThe XUlo-Oerman rejection was a\nMow to British and French hopes for\na peaceful solution of the crisis which\ngrew out of the Spanish civil war.\nIt was a slap at Soviet Russia.\nMoscow had accused Italy of tor\npedoing two Soviet freighters in the\neastern Mediterranean. The charge\nthreatened a diplomatic breach be\ntween Russia and Italy.\nBecause of refusal of Italy and\nGermany to take part in the parley\nit was expected the conference site\nwould be shifted from Nyon, Switzer\nland, to Geneva.\nAlthough Britain was determined to\nend the piracy, of which she had\nbeen a principal victim, her delegates\nwere understood to have been in\nstructed to do nothing at Friday's\ngathering to divide Mediterranean\ncountries into Fascist and Anti\nFascist blocs.\nMay Sever\nRumors\u2014totally without confirm\nation bussed to and fro, among\nthem one to the effect that Italo\nRussian diplomatic relations would\nbe severed or trade boycotts applied\nbetween the Fascist and Communist\npowers as the result of the repeated\nSoviet accu\u00bbotlon\u00bb.\nThe talks to which Britain had\nnamed a strong delegation were ex\npec\nted to be confined largely to\ntechnical and thus far secret\u2014\nXVanco-Britlsh naval plans to re\nstore order to the Mediterranean.\nThe crisis, in which may be bedded\nthe seeds of the next world war, has\nsolidified the friendship of the major\nFascist powers, as opposed to the\nSoviet union.\n1J. 8. WONT\nRECOGNIZED BLOCKADE\nWashington, Sept. 9\u2014(JPy\u2014V. 8. of\nilcals said Thursday this govern\nment has not altered its refusal to\nrecognise a blockade of Spanish sea\nports.\nOfficials said they had reason to\nbelieve that American ships carrying\n'ion-contraband cargoes had called at\nthese ports, and would continue to\nply Spanish waters.\nThere should be no interpietation\nof a change in policy, they said, from\nthe navy's warning to American\nmariners of \"pirate\" craft in the\nMediterranean sea.\nThe warning, broadcast to every\nAmerican vessel with radio receivers,\nsaid:\n\"American ships operating in the\nMediterranean sea are warned that\nmerchant vessels of various countries\nhave recently been attacked in that\nsea by unidentified aircraft, surface\nvessels and submarines.\"\nPotato Marketing:\nPlans Get AAA OK\nBoisa, Idaho, Sept. 9.\u2014(*)\u2014Federal\npotato marketing agreements in Min\nnesota, Wisconsin, North Dakota,\nColorado, Nebraska, Wyoming, Maine,\nMichigan and Idaho received tenta\ntive approval of the Agricultural Ad\njustment Administration, E. J. Iddlngs,\ndirector of the University extension\nservice here, said be had been in\nformed.\nThe agreements would become ef\nfective if signed by half the handlers\nIn the areas and then approved by\nSecretary Wallace.\nTO ELECT ALDERMAN\nMinot. N. D., Sept. #.\u2014Minot's fifth\nward will hold a special election Nov.\n1 to name a successor to Alderman\nLong-Time Bismarck Scoutsr\nElected at Missouri Vallsy\nArea Meeting\nL. K. Thompson, long-time Bis\nmarck Scouter, is new chairman of\nthe Bismarck district of the Missouri\nValley area council, elected Tuesday\nnight at the annual district meeting\nhere. Thompson succeeds Dr. George\nM. Cons tans.\nto\nElected vice chairman were F.\nWaldo and J. W. Caln&n, both for\ntheir first terms.\nW.\nA. Payne was\nre-elected to a vice president's post.\nThompson, a member of the troop\ncommittee of troop 3 since 1931\nserved as treasurer of the Missouri\nValley area council In 1935-36. Both\nWaldo and Calnan are also veterans\nof Scout work.\nConstans, presiding at the meeting,\ncalled upon troop chairmen and\nchairmen of standing district com\nmlttees for reports of the year's ac\nttvtti&s.\n41S Merit Badges Issued\nReporting on advancements during\nthe past year, Netland said that 46\nScouts had been promoted to the\nsecond class rank, 30 to first class,\n30 to Star Scout, 16 to Life Scout and\n18 to Eagle Scout. Four hundred six\nteen merit badges were awarded.\nTotal enrollment at Camp Chan\nOwapi, Wildwood lake Scout camp,\nthis summer totaled 351, Bill Mc\nDonald, chairman of the camping\ncommittee reported. Of these Scouts,\n117 were from Bismarck, he said.\nH. O. Saxvik, chairman of the\norganization committee, declared\nconcerted effort should be made to\nenroll every available boy in Scouting\nthis year.\nFlans to have a deputy commis\nsioner assigned to eac\u00a3i three troops\nin the district were revealed by Ro\nbert \u00a3irkwood, district Scout com\nmii*l6wr, who said that last year\nfour men worked with him on his\nstaff, each contacting three troops a\nmonth.\nOther Chairmen Report\nOther district chairmen making re\nports were Richard Barry, advance\nment end national Jamboree Henry\nDuemeland, finance Bill McGraw,\nboard of review C. W. Leifur, lead\nership and training Mark Hollis,\nhealth and safety and Worth Lumry,\nand Walter Brophy, activities.\nReporting for troop committees\nwere: Lloyd Liliestrand, troop 3 Ro\nbert Kirkwood, troop 3 Harold Chaf\nfee, troop 4 C. W. Leifur, troop 5\nGeorge Will, troop 6 John Calnan,\ntroop 7 A1 Hartl, troop 8 John\nKaraslewicz, troop 9 John Calnan,\ntroop 10 Charles Liessman, troop 11.\nMembers of the nominating com\nmittee who brought In the names of\nthe new officers were Kelly Simon\nson, chairman, H. O. Saxvik and Sam\nMerrltt.\nJ. D. WILSOH BUI\n(HUM (MCE\nFormer N. D. RRC Worker Bound\nOver Here to Face Embez\nzlement Charges\nJ. D. Wilson, one-time employe In\nthe finance division of the North Da\nkota Rural Rehabilitation office, was\nin Burleigh county Jail Thursday fac\ning trial on charges of embezzlement.\nWilson, held here since his arrest\nTuesday night, was committed to\nJail on default of $2,500 bond when he\nwaived preliminary hearing and was\nbound over to district court by Jus\ntice of the Peace H. R. Bonny.\nWilson was charged with embez\nzlement of $300 \"on or about July 24\"\nfrom the North Dakota Rural Re'\nhabilltatlon corporation, \"a corpora'\ntion organized under the laws of\nNorth Dakota.\" The charges were\nbrought by States Attorney George\nRegister of Burleigh county.\nThe arrest was made by Deputy\nSheriff Carl R. Koeitzky on a war\nrant issued by Bonny Apr. 31.\nUntil last spring, Wilson had been\nemployed in the Rural Resettlement\nadministration's regional office at\nLincoln, Neb.\nBusiness Outlook Is\nGood, Says Dawes\nChicago, Sept. OPh-Former\nVice President Charles Gates Dawes,\nchairman of the board of the City\nNational Bank and Trust company\nssid Wednesday he foresaw \"a con\ntinuance of satisfactory general\nbusiness conditions despite recent\nstock price recessions.\"\nI see no indications in business\nof a lack of confidence,\" Gen. Dawes\nsaid, \"and I expect to see business\nconditions continue satisfactory this\nyear and next.\"\nFive French Fliers\nKilled in Air Crash\nBordeaux, France, Sept. 9.\u2014(JP\nThe bodies of five French army fliers\nwere recovered Thursday from the\nwreckage of a large fighting plane\nEarl Campbell, who resigned to move which crashed in flames Wednesday\nso Wlllistoa. night near the Bordeaux airport.\nWestern N. D. Land Values\nScout Head\nL. K. Thompeon\nTEACHER SHORTAGE\nIN RURAL SCHOOLS\nCONFRONTS STATE\nConference Will Be Held Here\nFriday to Consider Causes,\nRemedies\nAn emergency arising from the re\nported shortage of teachers willing to\naccept rural school positions prompted\nState Supestntedeat of pnhlie In\nstruction Arthur E. Thoinpsoh Thurs\nday to call a cohferenoe of North Da\nkota educators to be held here Fri\nday.\nInvited to the session are county\nsuperintendents of schools from\ncounties where the shortage of teach'\ners appears most acute presidents of\nthe state teachers' colleges Don\nLarln, Bismarck, of the U. S. re-em\nployment servloe, and M. E. Mc\nCurdy, Fsrgo, executive secretary of\nthe State Education association.\nThe shortage appears to be concen\ntrated in the southwest and south\ncentral portions of the state, although\nWalsh county In the northeastern\nsection has reported a need for eight\nteachers In order to open all rural\nschools, Thompson said.\nIBHBAIIOW WOHEY\nU. S. Allots $1,605,000 for 17,\n000-Acre Project Along\nYellowstone\nWashington, Sept. 9 The\npresident allotted $1,605,000 to the bu\nreau of reclamation Wednesday to\nconstruct the Glendive unit of the\nBuffalo Rapids project, expected to\nIrrigate about 17,000 acres of drouth\nblistered soil in eastern Montana.\nFormal notice of the allotment said\nthe money will be made available\nthrough the emergency relief act of\n1937. Of the total amount, $776,000\nwill be on a reimbursable basis.\nThe Glendive unit is a part of the\nseveral million dollar Buffalo Rapids\nproject which the reclamation bureau\nInvestigated with a $25,000 public\nworks allotment. The area involved is\napproximately 17,000 Irrigable acres\nof bottom land along the Yellowstone\nriver between Fallon and Upper Seven\nMiles creek near Glendive.\nOf the total allotment for the proj\nect, $829,000 will be expended for la\nbor, the bureau said, and \"all avail\nable relief labor\" in the area will be\nused.\nPioneer Businessman\nDies at Park River\nPark River, N. D., Sept. 9.\u2014JPy\u2014\nFuneral services will be held here Sat\nurday for James J. Dougherty, 79,\npioneer businessman, former state\nlegislator and first school teacher at\nI*rimore, who died at his home here\nWednesday.\nStart Fire Looking\nFor 'Lost' Kitten\nFond du Lac, Wis., Sept. 9\u2014\nThe Earl Barber family is com\nsiderlng the advisability of putting\na leash on Tommy, three-month\nold pet kitten.\nWhen Tommy disappeared\nsomeone suggested he might have\ncrawled Into a hole in the bot\ntom of the davenport. Matches\nused to explor the cavity set the\ndavenport afire Water liberally\npoured on the blaze soaked most\nof the room. The fire department\nwas called.\nWhen the excitement abated\nTommy was found nestling on a\nbedroom chair.\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE\nGermany and Italy Will Boycott Piracy Conference\nAND_FRM Thompson Heads\nLocal Scout Area\nCHINESE CLING TO\nI\nII\nDetachment of 4,000 Japanese\nReported Wiped Out Near\nPeiping\nWERE CAUGHT IN AMBUSH\nChinese Blockade Yangtze\nAmericans Flee From Air\nRaid in South China\n(By the Associated Press)\nChinese troops clung tenaciously to\ntheir main lines on all Shanghai\nfronts Thursday in the face of in'\ncessant and sustained attacks from\nthe combined Japanese army, air\nforce and navy.\nFrom Peiping came unconfirmed\nreports that a detachment of 4,000\nJapanese troops had been wiped out\nby a deadly Chinese ambush In the\nrocky hills west of that ancient city.\nThe Japanese line was said to have\nbeen thrust back five miles by the\nsudden Chinese onslaught.\nThree other incidents stood out In\nThursday's fighting in the Far East's\nundeclared war:\nChinese struck a new blow at\nthe Japanese navy by blocking\nthe upper reaches of the Yangtze\nriver with obsolete steamers and\nChinese Junks loaded with sand\nand concrete. The barrier ef\nfectively blocked, the Japanese\nfleet from spreading Its activi\nties far up river from Shanghai.\nThree one-pound shells crashed\ndirectly in front of the American\nconsulate-general, seriously in\njuring three Chinese civilians and\none British policeman.\nAmerican residents In the\nSouth China port of Fukien were\ndriven into underground bomb\nproof dugouts by a two-hour\nJapanese air raid. There were\nno American casualties.\nRush Reinforcements\nHeavy reinforcements were flowing\nthrough Peiping to Llanghsiang, 30\nmiles to the south, and to the sore\nly-menaced Japanese right flank in\nthe western hills around Mentouquo,\n25 miles to the west.\nThe steady stream of wounded Jap\nanese coming back from the front was\nalmost equally heavy. Several thous\nands have been brought here In the\nlast few days and last night a train\nload of wounded was evacuated to\nTangku, the port of Tientsin, where\nthey will be sent back to Japan.\nMost of the Injured were lying flat\non the floors of cattle cars.\nReliable Chinese reports from the\nMentoukuo front, where the whole\nJapanese operation is threatened by\na wide Chinese flank attack, said that\nthe 4,000 Japanese were drawn into\na trap by retreating Chinese.\nThe Japanese pursued the retreat\nfar into the maze of hills where the\nChinese have prepared almost lmpreg\nliable positions. Then, from their\nlairs on the hill\nNorth Dakota's Oldest Newspaper\nESTABLISHED 187S BISMARCK, N. D., THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 9, 1937 PRICE FIVE CENTS\ntops,\nthe Chinese\nswarmed down, riddling the Japanese\nwith machine gun fire and forcing\nthem to retreat five miles to the east.\nRaid Endangers Lives\nAmerican lives were gravely en\ndangered and the United States war\nship Asheville was caught in the\nbombardment in South China. Sev\neral bombs fell only a short distance\nfrom the Asheville and forced her\nofficers and crew to hurry below\ndecks for refuge from the hail of\nshrapnel.\nBombs and shells from the Japan\nese planes and ships rained on the\narmy headquarters, police headquart\ners, the airfield and the old 'fort near\n(Continued on Page Two)\nWANTS FOREST PROJECT\nMitchell, Sept. 9.\u2014(#)\u2014Money for\ndevelopment of the proposed Sand\nHills National forest project In Brown\nand Marshall counties of South Da\nkota and two counties In North Da\nkota was sought Thursday by Sen\nator Herbert E. Hitchcock (Dem.,\nS. D.).\nBy KENNETH W. SIMONS\nTwo of the finest irrigated farms\nin the Lower Yellowstone valley are\nthose of Nels E. Back and Clayton\nWorst, son of Dr. J. H. Worst, for\nmer president of the North Dakota\nAgricultural collegf.\nTwo of the most successful irri\ngation ventures in North Dakota are\nthose on the penitentiary farm here\nand that of H. J. Houser, just south\nof the Missouri river bridge at\nSanish.\nAn impartial survey of these four\nfarms, made with an eye only to\nascertaining the facts, proves two\nthings.\nThe first is that North Dakota soil\ncan be made to grow\u2014is in fact grow\ning\u2014products comparable In quan\ntity and quality with those grown in\nMontana.\nThe second is that Irrigation in\nNorth Dakota will have to be simpli\nfied and put on a sounder basis or\nthe job of watering the land on this\nside of the line will cost so much as\nto make success a doubtful matter.\nWife's Plea to Franco\nMay Free U. S. Flier\nDahl and Bride\nChicago Paper Says 'Rapidly\nCrowing Army' Plans to\nTake Over Government\nChicago, Sept. 9.\u2014W)\u2014The Dally\nTimes said in a copyright article\nThursday that \"in uniforms strangely\nuggestlve of those worn by Adolf Hit\nler's Nazi storm troops, a relatively\nsmall but rapidly growing army Is\npreparing for the American counter\npart of 'Der Tag' when It plans to\nseize control of the United States.\"\nThe newspaper said the article\nsuited from an \"exhaustive lnvesti\ngatlon of American Nazis.\"\nCALLS CHARGES\n'GREATEST JOKE' IN HISTORY\nAndover, N. J., Sept. 9.\u2014W)\u2014'The\ndirector of the German-American\nBund's camp Nordland called the as\nsertlon that American Nazis were\npreparing to seize control of the\nUnited States \"the greatest joke in\nhistory.\"\nYellowstone Forest\nFire Out of Control\nLivingston, Mont.. Sept. 9.\u2014W)\u2014A\nblaze reported out of control was rag\ning near the northeastern corner of\nYellowstone National Park early\nThursday after burning over 1,600\nacres of land.\nAn army of 650 fire fighters battled\nthe blaze.\nIrrigated N. D. Farms\nGrow Good Crops, Too\nTo take the good side first, com\npart the production here with that\nin Montana.\nGets Late Start\nHouser got started late. For sev\neral years he operated a seven-sere\ntruck patch almost in the shadow of\nthe bridge and did fairly well. This\nyear, with the help of the State\nWater Conservation commission he\nput in a larger system further down\nstream and there has 40 acres in pro\nduction. But installing the pump,\nbuilding a flume across the lowland\nimmediately adjacent to the river,\nleveling the land and other details\ntook time. He was a month late In\napplying his water.\nAnd when he did get started he\ncouldn't put water on all parts of his\nplace at once. By the time he got\naround to irrigating some sections of\nthe farm it was too late. They\nhtven't received water yet.\nBut where the water was used\u2014\nparticularly where it was used\nearliest. Houser is getting a good\n(Continued as Pise Two)\nBurgos, Spain, Sept. 9\u2014(IP)\u2014Harold\nDahl, 28-year-old Champaign, 111\ncaptive airman who is under sentence\nof death, told the Associated Press\nThursday that Insurgent Generalis\nsimo Francisco Franco has promised\nhis release.\nThe promise was made to Dahl's\nbride of less than a year, who is now\nliving at Cannes, Ranee, Dahl was\nInformed.\nA personal letter from Mrs. Dahl\ndirect to the Generalissimo, enclosing\nher picture, did what official negoti\nations were not able to accomplish.\nDahl, who balled out of his blaz\ning Spanish government plane when\nIt was shot down by Insurgents July\n12, was so worried about his fate that\nhe refused to tell reporters his name\nuntil he learned of the plan for his\nfreedom.\nFranco wrote Mrs. Dahl that her\nhusband was in good health In an In\nsurgent prison and added that his\nlife \"never was in danger.\"\nHe suggested that Mrs. Dahl get\nin touch with the Spanish central\ngovernment, and tell of Franco's\npromise to exchange the aviator.\nThe Insurgent generalissimo agreed\nto send Dahl to France immediately\nin exchange for any Insurgent aviator\nheld prisoner by the government\nStormy Petrel of\nAir Waves in City\nW. K. Henderson, one-time stormy\npetrel of the air lanes when he was\noperating station KWKH at Shreve\nport, La., was a visitor in Bismarck\nThursday. He is on a trip into north\nern states to invite residents of this\nregion to come to Louisiana and view\nthe wonders and beauties of the\nsouth.\nBroke after a series of business re\nverses he says he has learned that a\nman can live without money and can\nbe as happy without it as he can\nwith it.\nN D. Water\nWin Endorsement\nCLAi NAZIS READY\nTO SEIZE CONTROL\nBroad Program for All of West\nern Part of State Approved\nby Association\nEndorsement of the water develop\nment program for Western North Da\nkota as presented by the North\nDakota Water Conservation commis\nsion was voted by members of the\nWestern North Dakota Reclamation\nassociation at a meeting in the capltol\nWednesday.\nAt the same time it was agreed\nmembers of the association would\ncontinue to enlist the interest of citi\nzens In water conservation projects\neach in his own community in an\neffort to unite public opinion behind\nthe board.\nSpeakers stressed the point that\neveryone agrees something must be\ndone about the lack of agricultural\nproduction due to Insufficient rainfall\nbut that not everyone agrees as to\nwhat should be done about it. Those\nat the meeting, however, reported a\nstrong demand for irrigation in their\ndistricts, some of the western coun\nties suggesting that they be given\nattention and that all attention not\nbe centered on developments along\nthe Missouri river.\nProgram Presented\nThe water board program as It re\nlates to Western North Dakota was\npresented as follows:\n1. Small Irrigation projects on all\nwestern watersheds ss fast as they\ncan be developed and financed.\n2. Co-operation with the bureau of\nreclamation In a study of the Tren\nton-Buford project near Williston and\nan effort to have this financed by the\ngovernment if the project Is proved\nby such studies to be sound.\n3. Development of irrigation, both\nIn the Missouri river valley and tri\nbutary streams, as rapidly as possible,\ngiving preference to those projects\nwhich are most sound from an eco\nnomic standpoint.\nConsider Well Supplies\n4. Development of irrigation water\nsupplies from wells in those areas\nwhere an adequate water supply is\nfound at depths which do not exceed\nan economic lift.\n5. Continuance of studies on all\nwestern watersheds looking to their\ncomplete development, largely by\ngovernment funds, but giving such\nstate aid as is necessary and possi\nble.\nOne of the chief speakers at the\nsession was Senator Gerald P. Nye, a\nmember of the senate committee on\nreclamation and irrigation, who ex\npressed himself as wholeheartedly for\nthe water conservation and irrigation\nprogram but warned that things move\nslowly in congress and that persist\nence will be necessary to achieve the\ngoal of a sound development.\nInexperience Is Handicap\nW. W. McLaughlin, Berkeley. Calif.,\nchief of the bureau of agricultural\nengineering in the department of ag\nriculture and a strong advocate of\nirrigation in Western North Dakota,\noutlined what he conceived to be a\nsound development program. He as\nsured those present that there are\ngreat possibilities here but warned\nthat it would be unwise to attempt\nto move too swiftly since it requires\nmen as well as land and water to\n(Continued on Page Two\nNEWS\nFrom the Fronts\nWashington\u2014Secretary Hull indi\ncated the United States does not in\ntend to withdraw its troops from\nChina so long as the present unde\nclared war between Japan and China\ncontinues.\nHendaye\u2014Insurgent planes and\nguns pounded government de\nfenses in Northwest Spain after\ntheir advance on Gijon had been\nstalled and more than 1,000 of\ntheir men killed In a sudden\ncounter-offensive.\n.London The 1019-ton British\nfreighter Stanwold reported she was\ncaptured by a Spanish Insurgent war\nvessel in the Bay of Biscay, Lloyd's\ndisclosed.\nNew York Gen. Francisco\nFranco was asked by 26 promi\nnent American and Canadian\nleaders to spare the lives of 2,000\ncaptured civilians said to be fac\ning execution for remaining loyal\nto the Madrid government.\nNanking\u2014U. 8. Ambassador Nelson\nJohnson ordered the American con\nsulate at Swatow closed and all\nAmericans evacuated because of the\nincreasing danger from Japanese\nbopibardment of the important South\nChina port.\nTokyo\u2014A Domei news agency\nreport from Shanghai said that\n100 Soviet trucks loaded with\nairplanes had arrived at Sianfu,\nChina, Shensi province capital.\nCASEY'S FUNERAL\nIS SET FOR FRIDAY\nRetired Railway Conductor Wil\nBe Buried in St. Mary's\nFollowing High Mass\nFuneral services for Patrick C. Ca\nsey, retired Pennsylvania railway\nconductor who died at his home here\nTuesday night, will be at 9 a. m. Frl\nday In St. Mary's procathedral. Bur\nial will be in St. Mary's cemetery.\nDavid Burge of Pittsburgh, a step\nson, will arrive by plane Thursday\nnight to attend the services, a requiem\nhigh mass.\nPallbearers will be Clarence Lar\nson, Max Kupltz, Harvey Crane, Ole\nJohnson, Joseph L. Kelley and Harry\nHoman.\nThe body will lie in the Convert Fu\nneral Home until time for services.\nAlthough Mr. Casey spent the ma\njority of his life in the east, he came\nto Bismarck in 1909 to settle the\ntate of a relative. Liking the coun\ntry he remained here.\nMr. Casey had a wide acquaintance\namong the older residents of Bis\nmarck. He was known as an avid\nsportsman.\nBesides the stepson, he also leaves\na stepdaughter, Mrs. Charles Smith of\nPittsburgh and a grandson, W. El\nBerwman of Bismarck, commissioner\nof the N. D. workmen's compensation\nbureau, and Mrs. Berwman.\nF. B. Heath Attending\nObservance in Minot\nF. B. Heath, president of the Dakota\nNational Bank and Trust company of\nBismarck, accompanied by W. B. Al\nlen of Chicago, second vice president\nof the Continental-Illinois National\nand Trust company, and Ray Madsen,\nMandan, president of the First Na\ntional bank, left for Minot Hiursday\nto participate in the observance there\nof the 40th anniversary of Minot's\nFirst National bank and the 86 years\nthat R. E. Barron, president, has\nserved that institution.\nOthers attending are J. Cameron\nThomson, Minneapolis, president of\nthe Northwest Bancorporatlon Blend\ning Fisher, Devils Lake, president of\nthe Ramsey County National bank\nTrygve Oas, Minneapolis, trust officer\nof the Midland National Bank and\nTrust company A. L. Netcher, Fargo,\npresident of the North Dakota Bank\ners association and the Northern and\nDakota Trust company C. C. Wattam,\nFargo, secretary of the North Dakota\nBankers association R- E. McGregor,\nMinneapolis, vice president of the\nNorthwestern National Bank and\nTrust company.\nWilliston Fugitive\nGuilty of Murder\nSpokane, Wash., Sept. 9.\u2014VPi\u2014Her\nbert Allen, 21, captured after a Jail\nbreak at Williston, N. D., pleaded\nguilty Wednesday to a first degree\nmurder charge growing out of a Spo\nkane bank robbery killing Feb. 15.\nA Jury must sentence him to death\nor life imprisonment. Two other\nyouths already are under the death\nsentence for the crime.\nSteer Prices Rise to\nNine-Year-Old Level\nChicago, Sept. 9.\u2014W\u2014Steer prices\nbridged the depression Thursday and\nequalled a price paid more than nine\nyears ago.\nPrime steers, 17 of them weighing\n1,221 pounds each, sold at $18.75 a\nhundred pounds in the Chicago Union\nstockyards, the highest price steers\nhid brought there since January.\n1926.\nThe Weather\nCloudy, partly cloudy\ntonight and Friday\ncooler.\nPARED BY BOARD\nOF EQUALIZATION\nBurleigh Valuation Raised ID\nPer Cent, Then Comes Un\nder Blanket Reduction\nSTATE TOTAL $548,225,411\nIs $21,348,050 Under 1936\nValuation Cut Applies\nin 31 Counties\nA blanket reduction of two per cent\non farm land valuations In 31 Central\nand Western North Dakota counties\nwas made Thursday by the state\nboard of equalization.\nTotal valuation of farm lands as set\nby the board for 1937 Is $548,335,411, a\nreduction of $15,900,178 under the fig\nures as submitted by county boards,\nand approximately $21,348,050 below\nthe 1936 valuation.\nThe reduction applies on the tenta\ntive figures adopted by the board after\na hearing several days ago. The board\nalso raised the valuation in Cavalier\n10 per cent, in Pembina 15 per cent,\nin LaMoure county 10 per cent, and in\nBurleigh county 10 per cent from the\nfigures set at the previous meeting.\nBurleigh county subsequently came\nunder the blanket 2 per cent reduc\ntion.\nRaise R. R. Valuation\nRailroad valuations were raised\nfrom (119,019,861 In 1936 to $120,768,\n163. Other utility property was scal\ned upward.\nCounties in which the two per cent\nblanket reduction apply are: Rollette,\nBottineau, Renville, Burke, Divide,\nWilliams, Mountrail, Ward, McHenry,\nPierce, Sheridan, McLean, Dunn, Mer\ncer, Oliver, Billings, Golden Valley,\nSlope, Bowman, Stark, Hettinger\nAdams, Grant, Morton, Sioux, Bur\nleigh, Kidder, Emmons, Logan, Mcin\ntosh, McKenzie.\nValuations of telegraph propertiei\nwere increased from $803,236 last\nyear to $918,236 and commercial tele\nphone oompeny valuations Jumped\nfrom $6,773,to $7,360,064.\nRaise Other UUUUos\nOther utility properties were wised\nas follows: Pullman Company, from\n$378,000 to $425,000 Railroad Bgpwi\nagency $100,000 to $316,500 electric,\ngas, heat, power and water, $16,000,456\nto $17,367,897. street railway proper\nties were valued at $62,000, the same\nas last year.\nValuations were set for tho first\ntime on private railway carlines, un\nder a 1937 legislative enactment, at\n$228,157 and on airlines at $78,986.\nChanges in railroad valuations as\nmade by the board from the 1936 fig\nures follow: Great Northern, in\ncreased from $63,791,327 in 1936 to\n$64,500,317 in 1937 Northern Pacific\n$41,238,350 to $42,240,369 Soo Line,\n$8,406,199 to $8,600,188 Chicago, Mil\nwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific $4,000,\n407 to $4,700,219 Midland Continental,\n$51,997 to $100,561.\nOther Boosts Given\nValuation of the Chicago and\nNorthwestern remained at $126,900\nwhile the valuation of the Brandon,\nDevils Lake and Southern was re\nduced from $139,999 to $99,999 and\nthe Farmers Grain and Shipping Co.,\nfrom $565,163 to $400,000.\nValuations of the Farmers Elevator\nspur at Mai da and the E. I. Donovan\nspur were set at $286 and $322, re\nspectively, the same as in 1936.\nFixing of the state tax levy is ex\npected to be done within the next\nweek or ten days. State Tax Commis\nsioner Owen T- Owen said.\nRemaining for final determination\nby the board is the valuation of city\nand village real estate.\nA reduction of $783,848 was made\nin personal property valuations for\nthe state. The 1937 personal prop\nerty valuation totals $105,381,916 com\npared to $106,166,764 in 1936.\nAb Jenkins Breaks\nMotor Speed Marks\nBonneville Salt Flats, Utah. Sept.\n9\u2014(/P)\u2014'Unsettled weather continued\nover Western Utah Thursday and Ab\nJenkins, American long- distance\nspeed driver, did not know when he\nwould resume his dash again.\nDuring the two hours and five min\nutes Jenkins hurled his huge \"Mor\nmon Meteor\" over the salt flat\nWednesday before rain halted hit\nprojected 48-hour run, he covered\n350.112 miles at an average of 168.09\nmiles an hour. He broke eight speed\nrecords ranging from 50 to 500 kilo\nmeters.\nBismarck Moistened\nSlightly by Showers\nOnly .03 of an inch of rain had\nfallen in Bismarck at 10 a. m. Thurs\nday as clouds still cut off the direct\nrays of the sun to make the Mis\nsouri Slope considerably cooler\nWednesday when the mer cur\ntouched a high of 91.\nCarrlngton, Jamestown, Min\nDevils Lake and Fargo also\nshowers, none of them totaling\nthan .05 Inches of precipitation.\nThe forecast was cloudy to\ncloudy Thursday night and\nand cooler.\nBANK DIRECTOR D1\nBordeaux, Ranee, Sept.\nPierre Quesnay, 44,\nof the Bank for InU\ntlements, was drowned\nwhile swimming in e peat\n\"Ulsfe of Saint fnapsfr \"7","height":"27104","width":"20864"}}
